	<div>
		<div class="comment_header">
		Comment <a href="#c_1713683363">358</a> by James Blake
		posted on 7/11/2008 at 7:48 PM
		</div>
		<div class="comment_text"><p>I've used a packet sniffer to look at what is happening (full details &lt;A HREF="<a href="http://disq.us/url?url=http%3A%2F%2Fjimmyblake.com%3AfNPLRqwB1XRBayct9aXyTmLxehU&amp;cuid=3321886" rel="nofollow noopener" title="http://jimmyblake.com">http://jimmyblake.com</a>"&gt;here&lt;/A&gt;.  Basically the -9838 is, as someone pointed out earlier, a cannot connect to the iTunes Music Store via SSL.</p><p>I've look at the request and response packets via the sniffer and effectively the iTMS server is sending a HTTP Error 500-13 message, which is 'Server too Busy.  What this means is there are just too many people trying to connect for the amount of available network connections to the server.  iTunes then converts this into the -9838 message we are all seeing.</p><p>If you manage to get a progress bar, this means the connection has been established to the iTMS (you are beyond the -9838) and you should leave it to takes its course.</p><p>For some people it seems to work (not for me unfortunately) but some are bombing out with a -4 error - which is a timeout.  If iTunes doesn't receive the activation response back from the iTMS within a given period iTunes will exit with this error.</p><p>So effectively, no matter what you click before you try activation on iTunes will help in the slightest.  You just have to keep pounding away until you get a slot and hope that the iTMS can process the activation before it times out.</p><p>Annoying thing is that I already have activated my new iPhone 3G once with no problems, but I have to reset it after cocking up the synchronisation and ending up with masses of duplicates.</p><p>:(</p><p>Good luck guys.</p></div>
	</div>
